# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
The intuition behind this solution is to construct a graph where each airport is a node, and there's a directed edge from one airport to another if there is a valid flight ticket from the first airport to the second. The goal is to find a valid itinerary that visits all the airports exactly once and returns it in lexical order.
# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
The approach used in the code is **Depth-First Search (DFS)** to explore possible routes. The flight function builds a graph representation of the tickets, and the dfs function performs the **DFS traversal starting from the "JFK" airport**. During the traversal, it keeps picking the **smallest lexical airport (due to the use of a priority queue)** from the available options and continues exploring until there are no more options. This ensures that the final ans vector will contain a **valid itinerary in lexical order**.
# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
1. Constructing the graph (in the flight function) takes **O(n)**, where n is the number of flight tickets.
1. The **DFS traversal** (in the dfs function) explores each airport at most once, so it takes **O(n)** time as well.
1. Reversing the ans vector takes **O(n)**.
1. Overall, the time complexity of the code is **O(n)**.

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
1. The code uses an **unordered map f** to store the graph representation, which can take up to **O(n)** space since there can be a ticket for each unique airport.
1. The **priority queue** for each airport can have a maximum of n entries (in the worst case), so the space complexity of the priority queues is also **O(n)**.
1. The **ans vector** can also take up to **O(n)** space.
1. Overall, the space complexity of the code is **O(n)**.

**In summary, the code efficiently finds a valid itinerary in lexical order using a graph representation and DFS traversal. It has a time complexity of O(n) and a space complexity of O(n).**

