# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
The intuition behind this solution is to construct a graph where airports are nodes, and directed edges represent flight routes. Then, perform a depth-first search (DFS) starting from the “JFK” airport while ensuring that you use all the given tickets and choose the lexicographically smallest path when multiple options are available.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
1.	Build a directed graph where the keys are departure airports, and values are lists of arrival airports. Sort these lists lexicographically.
2.	Initialize an empty list for the itinerary.
3.	Start the DFS from “JFK”, repeatedly choosing the smallest lexicographically destination while removing edges as you go.
4.	Reverse the final itinerary since DFS appends nodes in reverse order.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
•	Constructing the graph takes O(NlogN), where N is the number of tickets. Sorting the destinations for each airport takes O(NlogN) in total.
•	The DFS traversal explores each edge exactly once, taking O(N) time.
•	Overall, the time complexity is O(NlogN) for graph construction and O(N) for DFS, resulting in O(NlogN) in total.

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
•	The space complexity is dominated by the graph data structure, which requires O(N) space for storing the airport nodes and their destinations.
•	Additionally, the DFS call stack can go as deep as the number of tickets, resulting in a space complexity of O(N).
•	Overall, the space complexity is O(N).

